# DataHoover – Core Rules (Always Apply)

## Prime directive
Correctness > reproducibility > speed. Small diffs. Run tests after each change.

## Repo invariants
- Never commit generated data artifacts:
  - data/raw/**, data/state/**, *.duckdb, *.zip snapshots
- Local-first storage:
  - Raw snapshots -> data/raw/<source>/<timestamp>.<ext>
  - State/cache -> data/state/<source>.json
  - Normalized tables -> data/warehouse.duckdb (DuckDB)

## Connector contract (for every new source)
- Implement a connector module under src/datahoover/ (e.g., src/datahoover/connectors/<name>.py).
- Network hygiene:
  - Always set timeouts and a clear User-Agent.
  - Use conditional requests (ETag / If-None-Match or Last-Modified / If-Modified-Since) when possible.
- Idempotent writes:
  - The same ingest run should not duplicate rows.
  - Prefer upsert semantics keyed by (source, natural_id, observation_time).

## Testing rules
- Tests MUST NOT hit the network. Use mocking (httpx mocking) for fetchers.
- Keep a minimal smoke test for each connector’s normalization/parsing.

## Operational workflow
- After changes:
  - run: python -m pytest
  - run one ingest command end-to-end
  - confirm: hoover show-latest --limit 5

## Terminal permissions policy (DataHoover)

- Default: run commands without extra permissions (sandbox).
- If a command needs internet (pip installs, hoover ingest, curl/wget to known URLs):
  request ONLY: required_permissions: ["network"].
- If a command modifies git state (.git) such as commit/checkout/merge/pull/fetch:
  request ONLY what’s needed: ["git_write"] and add ["network"] only if remote is contacted.
- Never request ["all"] unless:
  (a) the sandbox prevents required functionality and
  (b) you explain exactly why, and
  (c) you show the full command for explicit approval.
- Never run risky commands (rm -rf, sudo, curl|sh) without explicit user confirmation.

